    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h1 id="Advanced-Statistics"><a href="#Advanced-Statistics" class="headerlink" title="Advanced Statistics"></a>Advanced Statistics</h1><h3 id="Transformations-of-Random-Variables"><a href="#Transformations-of-Random-Variables" class="headerlink" title="Transformations of Random Variables"></a>Transformations of Random Variables</h3><p>Let me set the example;<br>You have two independant random variables $X$ with pdf $f_{X}(x)$ and $Y$ with pdf $f_{Y}(y)$.<br>You will have a new random variable $Z$, where $Z=X-Y$, and say we want to calculate the marginal pdf of $Z$.<br><a id="more"></a><br>First we need to make a new joint pdf including Z, to avoid cluterization of the same random variables, lets first let give $X$ a different name, i.e. $X=W$.<br>Now we saw that we have $Z=X-Y$, but now its $Z=W-Y$.<br>We want to know our variable $Y$, so we re-arrange the above to get $Y=W-Z$.</p>
<p>Now, we use something called a <code>Jacobian</code>, and we will use its determinant to transform from $(x,y)$ to $(w,z)$, and then we can get the marginal pdf of $Z$.<br>So the jacobian is:<br>$$|J|=|\frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial(w,z)}|=\begin{vmatrix}<br>\frac{\partial x}{\partial w} &amp; \frac{\partial y}{\partial w} \\\<br>\frac{\partial x}{\partial z} &amp; \frac{\partial y}{\partial z}<br>\end{vmatrix}$$<br>We can then do the following:<br>$$f_{Z,W}=f_{X,Y}(w,w-Z)|J|$$<br>$$=f_{X}(w)f_{Y}(w-z) \cdot |J|$$<br>And then finally, to find the marginal pdf of $Z$, we intergrate out w from the joint pdf:<br>$$f_{Z}(z)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f_{X}(w)f_{Y}(w-z)dw$$</p>
